photo.title: Financial District from Coit Tower, Pioneer Park, Telegraph Hill, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content: To British eyes, US urban zoning like this looks bizarre. The foreground comprises residential streets of three-storey houses with the characteristic San Francisco bay windows (themselves reminiscent of British 20th Century suburban architecture), blending into a narrow band of two-storey office buildings. Then, as abruptly as crossing Washington Street, there rises a wall of high-rise towers including the 48-storey Transamerica Pyramid. Designed by William Pereira & Associates and built 1969-72 for the Transamerica Corporation, the distinctive 260m-tall Transamerica Pyramid was once ranked amongst the world's five tallest buildings; it's now 'merely' the tallest in San Francisco, clearly visible from across the region. It was nearly the world's second tallest, at 305 m (1,000 feet), but the City's Planning Commission was concerned about the view from Nob Hill, off the right of the image. Planning concerns also inspired its tapered shape, which reduces the building's apparent shadow and allows more light to penetrate to street level. The 'wings' rising from the 29th floor accommodate unavoidably vertical elements of the building: two elevator shafts on the east, and a stairwell and a smoke tower on the west. To the immediate right of the Pyramid is Montgomery Street, the original heart of the Financial District and "the Wall Street of the West". As recently as 1830 it was the waterfront, at which ships were able to moor; everything to the left is reclaimed land. Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in the 19th Century; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s. [Image features several notes]

photo.title: Trouble in paradise

description._content:
Got a chance to test out the new Sony A7R + Metabones Smart Adapter III + 17 TS-E. The A7R has performed quite well up until now, but it appears the combo flares badly if there are bright lights just outside of frame.

After some investigating, it appears that stray light from the 17 TS-E's large image circle will bounce off the ribbed inner surface of the Metabones Smart Adapter III, causing a blooming effect.  You can easily replicate this by framing a shot that flares at the edge, then unmounting the camera from the adapter while it is still on the tripod (being careful not to disturb the framing of the lens).  If you look straight through the adapter, you should find a bright spot inside the adapter opposite the direction of the lightsource.  Im not sure why Metabones did not design a wider optical path or use a more light absorbent material like the black velvet in most lens or teleconverters.

Its not a showstopper since the problem is visible in liveview and you can just reframe slightly or blocking it with your hand.  However it might be time to start looking for a true FF adapter... or a native F-E mount UWA....

(4 second exposure)

photo.title: An Auspicious Horizon

description._content: This image of the gorgeous San Francisco skyline at night  is the first skyline I captured with my Nikon D90. This was my first visit to the city by the bay and after hearing so much hype and great things over the years, I can truly say San Francisco did not disappoint. It is an amazing city with a wealth of things to experience and enjoy. I have been to both Los Angeles and San Diego a zillion times and left San Francisco much more impressed and amazed. Keep in mind, growing up near Seattle, San Francisco probably appealed to me more because Seattle and San Francisco have some obvious similarities in their topography, make-up, and history (both gold rush cities). This image was captured on Telegraph Hill with Coit Tower resting behind me and in the center of the image is the famous landmark, the Transamerica Pyramid. I plan on visiting this city several more times and was so impressed to be able to finally capture this image. Enjoy!

photo.title: San Francisco - Financial District: 345 California Center and The American International Building

description._content:
345 California Center (left), also known as the First Interstate Center, or by locals as the Tweezer Towers, at 345 California Street, was built in 1986 by Skidmore, Owings & Merrill.  The mixed use postmodern complex consists of two 695-feet high towers linked by glass "sky bridges."  The Mandarin Oriental Hotel (called "MO") occupies the top eleven floors with the address of 222 Sansome.  It is is the tallest mid-block skyscraper in San Francisco. By placing the building in the middle of the block, developers were able to preserve four historic buildings, one at each corner.  The JH Dollar Building and the Robert Dollar Building, both former headquarters for large shipping companies, are located at the northwest and northeast corners of the block.  220 Sansome Street and 200 Pine are located at the southwest and southeast corners of the block.

The American International Building (right), also known as 220 Sansome Street, is a 16-story high-rise commercial building.

photo.title: 345 California Center Financial District San Francisco 150506-105125 C4e

description._content:
You can see 345 California Center from various parts of the city of San Francisco. This image of the 48 story financial district building was captured from the 6th floor of 435 Market Street while Melody and I were waiting for a class to assemble at the Small Business Development Center. Consequently, this is not a typical view of the 345 California Center Building. Image captured with my Canon Powershot SX50 through  thick high rise glass of the room we were in.
Unless one uses an expensive architectural camera, there will be several slanted edges in photos of buildings. I usually try to edit such photos to have some significant straight line. Here I obviously concentrated on the main 345 California Center building. Not everything can or needs to be straight or level - but I think the illusion of such is important to achieve some feeling of balance.

photo.title: Telegraph Hill and the Financial District from San Francisco Bay, Ca. USA

description._content:
This view from offshore highlights why the 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf (Pier 39 is at the right of the foreground) and the Financial District (in the background) was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships.  Within three years it had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the 'Telegraph Hill' name stuck.  The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent further development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park.  Aside from being an obvious choice for the location of the 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, opened in 1933, Pioneer Park is also known for its resident wild parrots.

Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in 1850; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s.  The skyline features four successively holders of the record for 'tallest building in California' (and hence tallest west of west of the Mississippi) 1964-74: at 142 m, the Hartford Building at 650 California St. was tallest when built in 1964, but surrendered the title to the 172 m 44 Montgomery (once the world headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank) on its completion in 1967.  555 California Street, still the second tallest building in the city and largest by floor area, reached 237 m in 1969, but was overtaken by the dramatic 260 m Transamerica Pyramid in 1972. That in turn is now 'merely' the tallest in the city and in the top 200 worldwide.
The city's third tallest, incidentally, is the twin-towered 345 California Center, 189 m tall to roof level but 220 m if the spires are included.

photo.title: 345 California Center

description._content: 345 California Center is third tallest skyscraper located in the Financial District of downtown San Francisco, California and it looked quite illuminated on this July day.  The 48-story, 695 foot building is known locally in San Francisco as the Tweezer Towers because of its tweezer shaped top.  It was completed in 1986 and is definitely one of San Francisco's architectural wonders that stands out amidst the Transamerica Pyramid.  The smaller sized square shaped windows give the building a very classy look and feel and the twin U.S. flags at the top definitely give the building an "American Pride" feel.  It is definitely a great feeling personally for me (with this upload) of getting back to my skyscraper roots.  This image was captured in July 2009 with my Nikon D90.  Enjoy!

photo.title: San Francisco - Financial District: 345 California Center

description._content:
345 California Center, also known as the First Interstate Center, or by locals as the Tweezer Towers, at 345 California Street, was built in 1986 by Skidmore, Owings & Merrill.  The mixed use postmodern complex consists of two 695-feet high towers linked by glass "sky bridges."  The Mandarin Oriental Hotel (called "MO") occupies the top eleven floors with the address of 222 Sansome.

This is the tallest mid-block skyscraper in San Francisco. By placing the building in the middle of the block, developers were able to preserve four historic buildings, one at each corner.  The JH Dollar Building and the Robert Dollar Building, both former headquarters for large shipping companies, are located at the northwest and northeast corners of the block.  220 Sansome Street and 200 Pine are located at the southwest and southeast corners of the block.
